<br>
You're taking things they have given / considered giving us for balancing our class and pointing out where / why they are wrong and aspects of them that could / should be changed.  It fits in with both class balance and general discussions, but would be better suited in this forum.  <br>
<br>
As to your original post.<br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them Harvest, but make it stun then for a long period of time, and make<br>
&gt; sure to implement it with a statement by Abashi that &quot;Wizards will be receiving<br>
&gt; some changes soon, but not because of any perceived lack in the class design.&quot;<br>
<br>
Do you use harvest?  I do.  The stun isn't very long, it feels like 5 real life seconds.  Harvest was a great addition to the class, though they could have scaled it much better for the 50-60 crowd.<br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them anti-gate (translocational suppression) spells, but it will <br>
&gt; silence them for 30seconds after casting.<br>
<br>
First of all, these never made it live because of the extreamly negative feedback.  Reality was that without the 30 second silence, one Wizard could chain cast these spells and take the risk of a mob gating out of the equation totally.  What people chose to leave out was that these spells had a .5 second casting time which allowed the Wizard to cast spells up until the end where he could cast the extreamly fast gate suppression spell and prevent the mob from gating.  Once the spell was cast that Wizard could sit and med for 30 seconds, and because the spell was cast when the mob was almost dead there would have been no loss of damage.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them a familiar, but make it cost them 1250hp/mana if it dies or poofs.<br>
<br>
It costs you approx 800 hp if it dies and that &quot;death&quot; will eat through your runes or epic shield.  The mana number works differently and I have a feeling it's a percentage of your current total mana.  You have also left out that we have the ability at 59 to turn these familiars invulnerable (even though I personally think they should be all together).  They are a situational spell, you must keep that in mind (like the Cleric self armor and the Mage self armor).<br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them Rain spells, but leave the 3rd wave broken for 3 years, thus<br>
&gt; eliminating any possible mana efficiency of the spell, and therefore group<br>
&gt; attractiveness as well. <br>
<br>
Please get your facts straight.  The third wave couldn't get kill shots, that was all.  If a mob was at half HP all waves would hit fine, it was when the mob got below 10% that the problems started.  Other than that the spell was fine.  Instead of using the rain spells at the end, use them mid-mob life and normal nukes at the end.<br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them awesome AE spells that are only useful in a group because of <br>
&gt; the need for chain-stun by an enchanter. But, if they every find a good zone <br>
&gt; to use it in, lets eliminate its use by totally destroying that zone.<br>
<br>
Read what you're saying again.  Imagine how POWERFUL Wizards would be if we could AE 30, 20, or even 10 mobs alone with no others.  Look at the other hand, an Enchanters PB stuns can't get put to maximum use w/o a Wizard.  <br>
<br>
Have you ever done AE in Sebilis, Karnors, or Chardok?  I have, I lived in AE seb from 56-60.  Those zones still work fine, I'm sure there are others that work great too.  The Grey incident isn't even worth getting into.  Anyone who has done AE there surely must admit that the nerf was partically called for.  My personal record there?  Around 86 mobs in ONE PULL with no risk and when they were all done we were still at 60% mana.  <br>
<br>
&gt; Let's give them a massive nuke series called BANE, but make it useful against<br>
&gt; only a handful of monsters in the game, difficult to get, and make it cost 20pp<br>
&gt; per cast.<br>
<br>
We also have 2 two new nukes (one larger than banes) brought in with the introduction of Shadows of Luclin.  Those &quot;handful of mobs&quot; were honestly the only ones banes were needed on.  2000 points of unresistable damage on a 32k HP mob would be a sick representation of class balance.  Can you say 16 Wizards killing ANY 32k mob?  Cost-wise, I don't aprove of it one bit.  They really should have re-examined that and made them componentless or at the very least 1 peridot.<br>
<br>
